---
import GeneExplorer from '../components/GeneExplorer'
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro'

// Shown verbatim in the "Build the same thing yourself" section. Kept as a
// frontmatter string (not inline JSX) so the braces/angle-brackets aren't
// parsed as Astro expressions inside <pre>. Mirrors buildSessionSpec() in
// src/lib/geneExplorer.ts.
const buildSnippet = `
// A JBrowse session is just an array of views, linked to each other by id.
// You open one by putting the spec in the URL — no server, no build step.
const spec = {
  views: [
    {
      type: 'LinearGenomeView',
      id: 'lgv',
      assembly: 'hg38',
      // the collapsed-intron trick: a loc made of the exon ranges,
      // space-separated, so the exons render back-to-back
      loc: 'chr17:7,673,534-7,673,608 chr17:7,673,700-7,673,837',
      tracks: ['hg38-ncbiRefSeqSelect'],
    },
    {
      type: 'MsaView',           // jbrowse-plugin-msaview
      connectedViewId: 'lgv',    // <- this is what links it to the genome view
      connectedFeature: feature, // the transcript model (CDS start/end/phase)
      msaIndexedLocation: { uri: MSA_URL },
      msaName: 'TP53',           // random-read this gene's block by name
      treeFileLocation: { uri: TREE_URL },
    },
    {
      type: 'ProteinView',       // jbrowse-plugin-protein3d
      connectedViewId: 'lgv',
      feature,
      url: 'https://alphafold.ebi.ac.uk/files/AF-P04637-F1-model_v6.cif',
    },
  ],
}

const url =
  JBROWSE + '?config=' + encodeURIComponent(CONFIG) +
  '&session=spec-' + encodeURIComponent(JSON.stringify(spec))
`.trim()
---

<Base
  title="JBrowse integration — JBrowseMSA"
  description="Type any human gene and get a connected JBrowse session: a collapsed-intron gene view, its 100-way protein alignment, and the AlphaFold structure — synthesized in the browser from a parsed GFF."
  wide
>
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>JBrowse integration</h1>
    <p>
      Type a human gene name. You get a connected JBrowse session with three
      linked views: the gene on the <strong>genome</strong> (introns collapsed so
      the coding exons sit side by side), the same protein{' '}
      <strong>aligned across 100 vertebrates</strong>, and its{' '}
      <strong>AlphaFold 3D structure</strong>. Hover or select in any one view
      and the other two light up the matching residue — codon-precise, across
      genome, alignment, and structure.
    </p>

    <GeneExplorer client:only="react" />

    <details>
      <summary>How it works (under the hood)</summary>
      <p>
        Nothing is precomputed per gene — the whole session is synthesized live
        in your browser from public data:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>mygene.info</strong> resolves the gene symbol to its hg38 locus
          and UniProt accession (and powers the type-ahead).
        </li>
        <li>
          The canonical (MANE / RefSeq Select) transcript is pulled by locus
          from the UCSC <code>ncbiRefSeqSelect</code> GFF over{' '}
          <strong>tabix</strong>, then the GFF is parsed in the browser — that
          is where the exon/CDS model comes from.
        </li>
        <li>
          The <strong>AlphaFold</strong> structure is fetched by UniProt accession.
          Only the 100-way alignment is a hosted file (a slice of a genome-scale alignment),
          random-read by gene name from an indexed bgzip FASTA.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        There is no <code>collapseIntrons</code> option in JBrowse. The trick is to
        give the Linear Genome View a <code>loc</code> made of the exon ranges, space-separated,
        so each renders back-to-back and the introns disappear. The alignment and
        structure stay in sync because all three views share the same transcript model,
        so a residue maps to its codon and back.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Build the same thing yourself</summary>
      <p>
        A JBrowse session is a declarative <em>spec</em>: an array of views,
        each pointing at the others by <code>connectedViewId</code>. You don't
        write any wiring code — you describe the views, put the spec in the URL,
        and the{' '}
        <a href="https://github.com/GMOD/jbrowse-plugin-msaview">msaview</a>{
          ' '
        }
        and{' '}
        <a href="https://github.com/GMOD/jbrowse-plugin-protein3d">protein3d</a
        >{' '}
        plugins handle the linking. The shape:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{buildSnippet}</code></pre>
      <p>
        That's the entire mechanism — every link in the{' '}
        <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/gallery#connected`}>gallery</a> is one
        of these URLs. The explorer above just fills in the{' '}
        <code>feature</code>, exon ranges, and accessions for whatever gene you
        type. The full source is{' '}
        <a
          href="https://github.com/GMOD/JBrowseMSA/blob/main/packages/website/src/lib/geneExplorer.ts"
          >geneExplorer.ts</a
        >{' '}
        (see <code>buildSessionSpec</code>), and the URL-param API is documented
        under{' '}
        <a href="https://jbrowse.org/jb2/docs/urlparams/">JBrowse URL params</a
        >.
      </p>
    </details>
  </article>
</Base>
